69
00:03:09.007 --> 00:03:13.000
Microservices are a way of building applications such

70
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.002
that they can be decomposed into smaller units of work.

71
00:03:17.002 --> 00:03:21.003
Spring Cloud thrives in a microservices architecture.

72
00:03:21.003 --> 00:03:23.005
And as such, there is a need for us

73
00:03:23.005 --> 00:03:26.007
to look at microservices in more depth.

74
00:03:26.007 --> 00:03:29.004
Most of these topics are covered in depth

75
00:03:29.004 --> 00:03:32.008
in my course Microservices Foundations here

76
00:03:32.008 --> 00:03:35.001
on the LinkedIn Learning catalog.

77
00:03:35.001 --> 00:03:37.009
One of the first basic things you should understand

78
00:03:37.009 --> 00:03:42.000
is the concept of domains and domain-driven development.

79
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.002
We will be building microservices-based applications

80
00:03:45.002 --> 00:03:47.004
using domain constructs.

81
00:03:47.004 --> 00:03:49.008
As such, an understanding of them

82
00:03:49.008 --> 00:03:52.008
will help you move forward in this course.

83
00:03:52.008 --> 00:03:54.009
Part of that understanding will help accept

84
00:03:54.009 --> 00:03:58.000
why Spring Cloud can be so needed

85
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.009
in a microservices-based architecture.

86
00:04:00.009 --> 00:04:04.001
You should understand why microservices are so powerful

87
00:04:04.001 --> 00:04:06.008
in a cloud made of architecture as well.

88
00:04:06.008 --> 00:04:09.003
And as such, this knowledge will help you understand

89
00:04:09.003 --> 00:04:11.000
why we are building applications

90
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.002
in this way for this course.

91
00:04:14.002 --> 00:04:16.008
Furthermore, I ask that you understand scaling

92
00:04:16.008 --> 00:04:21.006
in systems as a whole, specifically horizontal scaling.

93
00:04:21.006 --> 00:04:24.006
12-factor application methodologies are designed

94
00:04:24.006 --> 00:04:26.009
for cloud native applications.

95
00:04:26.009 --> 00:04:30.000
I have a course on LinkedIn Learning specifically

96
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.008
on understanding 12-factor application development.

97
00:04:32.008 --> 00:04:35.002
I encourage you to check it out.

98
00:04:35.002 --> 00:04:36.007
I would like you to know the basics

99
00:04:36.007 --> 00:04:39.009
of 12-factor applications from the perspective

100
00:04:39.009 --> 00:04:42.007
of what they mean for application development

101
00:04:42.007 --> 00:04:45.002
of cloud native applications.

102
00:04:45.002 --> 00:04:49.004
The details of each factor are not critical for this course,

103
00:04:49.004 --> 00:04:51.002
but they will be critical for you

104
00:04:51.002 --> 00:04:55.006
in building cloud native applications after this course.

105
00:04:55.006 --> 00:04:57.001
For the purposes of this course,

106
00:04:57.001 --> 00:04:58.005
you should understand the drive

107
00:04:58.005 --> 00:05:01.006
behind using externalized configuration.

108
00:05:01.006 --> 00:05:04.008
This knowledge will be integral to understanding the reasons

109
00:05:04.008 --> 00:05:07.000
behind the framework we will set up

110
